description:
So, this is a pretty important little story about Bootsy and a cane toad. It was 11:30 pm, I took the pups out. I looked over and Boots had a cane toad in her mouth. I scooped her up and called the emergency vet which is an hour away. After a crazy night of seizures, foaming at the mouth, and trips. Here is what I learned and important things to know: 
* if you see the toad, immediately flush the dogs mouth and do not let them swallow the water 
*induce vomiting with hydrogen peroxide 
*take a soft toothbrush and dip it in peroxide; brush the dogs tongue and gums; flush again
*if can, take dog to vet to get iv
*if can’t, monitors dog
* if dog survives first 30 minutes, they are out of the dark, just tripping and time will heal
Sorry for the long post, but it may save your baby!

🐾 IT’S NATIONAL PET DAY! 🐾
Many of you will know the joy and happiness that your pets bring you.

Here at Wee Critters we encourage everyone to thoroughly research any animal from a goldfish to a dog, before welcoming them to your home.

Unfortunately, a number of our Wee Critters came to us because they were no longer wanted or cared for. 

🐍Nagini the common boa was abandoned on the side of a main road and rescued by a friend of mine before coming to live with me. 🐍

🐸We were asked to rehome Trevor the cane toad and when he came to us he had not been fed for months.  He was starving and emaciated and we didn’t know if he would survive but with a healthy diet and some tlc he quickly became a much loved and happy member of our family.  He now lives happily with Ron and Neville our other Cane toads.  We think he is TOAD-ally awesome! 🐸

🦎Elliott the Argentine black and white tegu became too big for his previous owner and they could no longer give him the care that he needed.  He quickly settled into life with us and apart from being grumpy when he’s hungry he is a lovely big guy with a great personality! 🦎

🐢We have also provided a home for Theo and Esio Trot the tortoises.  Many people don’t realise how long tortoises live and it really is a lifelong commitment.  We were happy to add this pair to our family when their previous owners could no longer care for them. 🐢

We respect any individual who rehomes an animal when they realise that they cannot give it the care required and it is always vital to approach professionals who are more than willing to help.  There is never an excuse for abandoning a poor animal like Nagini was and we are just lucky she survived as we can’t imagine life without all of our wee critter friends.

Always think carefully before choosing any pet and consider whether you have the time, resources, space, experience and commitment to care for the animal. If you ever find yourself in a position that you can no longer care for a pet, approach someone responsible and qualified to assist you in finding the animal a suitable new home.

🌟 CANE TOAD 🌟
.
(Rhinella marina), also known as the giant neotropical toad or marine toad, is a large, terrestrial true toad.
.
💕SIZE AND LIFESPAN:
.
generally range in size from 6 to 9 inches in length.  can live upto 10 – 15 years In the wild
.
🏵DISTRIBUTION:
.
native to South and mainland Central America, but which has been introduced to various islands throughout Oceania and the Caribbean, as well as Northern Australia. 
.
🌳HABITATS:
.
inhabits open grassland and woodland, and has displayed a "distinct preference" for areas modified by humans, such as gardens and drainage ditches. In their native habitats, the toads can be found in subtropical forests, although dense foliage tends to limit their dispersal.
.
🌾FEEDING:
.
are omnivores and eat a variety of vegetation, insects, small birds, other toads or frogs, lizards, small mammals, and snakes.
.
☘BREEDING:
.
lay their eggs in still or slow flowing water. Females can produce between 8,000 – 35,000 eggs at a time and usually breed twice a year. The eggs hatch after a couple of days and tiny tadpoles emerge.
.
☠PREDATORS:
.
it has many natural predators. Caimans (a relative of the crocodile), snakes, birds, and even fish prey on the cane toad.
.
🟢CONSERVATION STATUS🟢
Least Concern (IUCN 3.1)
.
💡SCIENTIFIC CLASSIFICATION:-
.
Kingdom : Animalia
Phylum :  Chordata
Class : Amphibia
Order :  Anura
Family :  Bufonidae
Genus :  Rhinella
Species :  R. marina
.
.

Camouflage. Canetoads are brilliant at it. With ponds and puddles about to dry up throughout the Top End, if you have a permanent low water feature now is the time to really keep an eye on it as all water loving and reliant creatures will sniff it out. We often go spot lighting just after dark and I then check again early in the morning. Any canetoads found are turned into fertiliser.
It's also a great time to introduce a frog hotel (or maybe a few of them) to your garden to house green tree frogs through the dry season. By night the tree frogs will help to clear out the pesky foliage eating caterpillars that like your veggies.

Have you had heaps of Cane Toads with all of this rain? ⁠
⁠
Watergum’s Cane Toad Challenge revolutionises the control of this harmful and toxic pest by using the toad’s own toxins against them. It involves collecting adult cane toads and the trapping of tadpoles in tadpole traps using lures made from cane toad glands.⁠
⁠
To find out more visit the watergum.org/cane-toad-challenge, and get prepared for next season.

Cane toad leather!

I've been thinking about cane toads more than your average folk recently... The many possibilities of utilising this invasive species. 
Eating and tanning! 
My housemates (including 2 and 8 year old girls) collected bags full. We had a cane toad leg feast (highly recommended!) and chatted about tanning this cane toad.
I found a massive cane toad road kill that was salvageable and experimented with tanning it. I hadn't and neither had anyone I've spoken to, tanned an amphibian. 
So I tried fat tanned him. He needed a few redampenings to get soft but now with a good rub of dubbin he's lovely! He'll get a good smoke when the weather clears up. 
Such a tough skin for such a small fella. I'm impressed.
Skinning was easy enough, and I left the poison glands on as you can see. So incredible to see the white pus-y toxic excrete seep through the pores (don't worry, only an issue if you get it in your eyes or swallow it). And then see them dry.
The patterns of the cane toad are so beautiful. The textured back and the spotted belly.. Cane toad, you're a beauty.
I've got a dozen or so skins in the freezer from the feast, who knows what I might make with these skins.
I'm experimenting with euc barks for bark tanning. Though black she oak, banksia serratta and black wattle barks too once I hunt around for them. Have you heard some stories? Stories of the land, of tannins, of animals of this land? Let us share and grow together. 

Experimenting and playing, problem solving and creating, with our other than human kin, this is my happy place.

I'm holding an intro to tanning talk in a couple of weeks, in the Northern Rivers. If any of this tickles your fancy I hope you can join me.

It has been raining non-stop for days now.  The path to the nature lagoon was strewn with over turned toads with their intestines hanging out.  It appears that the birds have learned to flip them over before eating bits of them that is not poisonous.
A native of Central and South America, the cane toad (Rhinella marina) was introduced to Australia to control the cane beetles.  As it had no natural predators, it soon was over running tge entire continent.  The poison on its skin is toxic to all native wildlife.  It appears though that some native birds have adapted to turning them over beforemKing a meal out of them to avoid being poisoned

This here is Grouch our resident Cane Toad. He loves a little bit of sunshine! 

Cane Toads are an invasive species introduced to Australia in the early 1900’s. They have a toxin that seeps out of glands next to their eyes. We have grouch to help educate the public. He reminds people what his species can look like and the drastic effects his species can have on the native ones here in Australia.

Welcome back to #WildlifeWednesday!

This week, we present to you: the Cane Toad (Rhinella marinus).

The cane toad is a common, large but squat, terrestrial toad often found under street lighting in urban areas of Belize where there are abundant populations living alongside humans. They secrete a white milky poison from glands on each shoulder if threatened which can be very harmful to humans and lethal to domestic pets and other smaller animals.

DID YOU KNOW there are 37 (or maybe 38) species of amphibian in Belize? 35 species are frogs or toads, the remaining 2 (or 3) species are made up of salamanders like the Mexican climbing salamander.

We'll see you back here next week for more...

Getting to practice amphibian exams was “toad”ally awesome! 🐸
.
Cane toads are the largest species of toad and they pack a punch! They release a toxin from their parotid glands that can be deadly to pets and wildlife! ☠️
.
They’re also an invasive species in a number of locations throughout the United States. Cane toads eat everything and can outcompete native species for the resources they need to survive! 🙈
.
That’s why It is so important to do your research when purchasing a pet and to NEVER just release your pet into the wild. They can have lasting harmful impacts on the ecosystem. 🌎🌍🌏

ɪ ɢᴏᴛ ᴘᴏɪsᴏɴᴇᴅ ʙʏ ᴀ ᴄᴀɴᴇ ᴛᴏᴀᴅ ʟᴀsᴛ ɴɪɢʜᴛ. ɪᴛ ᴡᴀs ᴀ ʀᴏᴜɢʜ ɴɪɢʜᴛ, ʙᴜᴛ ɪ ᴀᴍ ʀᴇᴄᴏᴠᴇʀɪɴɢ ᴀɴᴅ ғᴇᴇʟɪɴɢ ʙᴇᴛᴛᴇʀ ᴛᴏᴅᴀʏ. 
 
ʜᴇʀᴇ ᴀʀᴇ sᴏᴍᴇ sᴛᴇᴘs ᴛᴏ ғᴏʟʟᴏᴡ ɪғ ᴀ ᴠᴇᴛ ɪsɴᴛ ᴀᴠᴀɪʟᴀʙʟᴇ. 
 
↠ ᴡᴀsʜ ᴍᴏᴜᴛʜ ᴡɪᴛʜ ᴡᴀᴛᴇʀ
 
↠ᴛɪʟᴛ ʜᴇᴀᴅ ᴅᴏᴡɴ, ᴀʟʟᴏᴡ ᴡᴀᴛᴇʀ ᴛᴏ ғʟᴏᴡ ᴏᴜᴛ ᴏғ ᴍᴏᴜᴛʜ, ɴᴏᴛ ᴅᴏᴡɴ ᴛʜᴇɪʀ ᴛʜʀᴏᴀᴛ 
 
↠ᴅᴏ ᴛʜɪs ᴄᴏɴᴛɪɴᴜᴀʟʟʏ / ᴘᴇʀɪᴏᴅɪᴄᴀʟʟʏ ᴛʜʀᴏᴜɢʜᴏᴜᴛ ᴛʜᴇ ᴏʀᴅᴇᴀʟ 
 
↠ᴅᴀᴍᴘᴇɴ ᴄʟᴏᴛʜ ᴡɪᴛʜ ʜʏᴅʀᴏɢᴇɴ ᴘᴇʀᴏxɪᴅᴇ ᴀɴᴅ ᴄʟᴇᴀɴ ʏᴏᴜʀ ᴅᴏɢs ᴍᴏᴜᴛʜ ᴀɴᴅ ɢᴜᴍs
 
↠ᴏᴘᴇɴ ᴅᴏɢs ᴍᴏᴜᴛʜ ᴀɴᴅ ғᴏʀᴄᴇ 2/3 sᴘᴏᴏɴs ᴏғ ᴛᴀʙʟᴇ sᴀʟᴛ ᴅᴏᴡɴ ᴛʜᴇɪʀ ᴛʜʀᴏᴀᴛs, ʏᴏᴜ ᴡᴀɴᴛ ᴛᴏ ᴍᴀᴋᴇ ᴛʜᴇᴍ ᴠᴏᴍɪᴛ ᴛᴏ ᴇxᴘᴇʟ ᴛᴏxɪɴs 
 
↠ᴀɢᴀɪɴ ᴏᴘᴇɴ ʏᴏᴜʀ ᴅᴏɢs ᴍᴏᴜᴛʜ ᴀɴᴅ ғᴏʀᴄᴇ 2 ᴄʜᴀʀᴄᴏᴀʟ ᴛᴀʙs ᴅᴏᴡɴ ᴛʜᴇɪʀ ᴛʜʀᴏᴀᴛs, ᴄʜᴀʀᴄᴏᴀʟ ᴡɪʟʟ ʟɪɴᴇ ᴛʜᴇɪʀ sᴛᴏᴍᴀᴄʜ ᴀɴᴅ ᴘᴏssɪʙʟʏ ʟɪᴍɪᴛ ᴛʜᴇ ᴀʙsᴏʀʙᴛɪᴏɴ ᴏғ ᴛᴏxɪɴs ɪɴᴛᴏ ᴛʜᴇ ʙʟᴏᴏᴅsᴛʀᴇᴀᴍ 
 
↠ᴋᴇᴇᴘ ᴡᴀsʜɪɴɢ ᴅᴏɢs ᴍᴏᴜᴛʜ, ᴀɴᴅ ᴋᴇᴇᴘ ᴛʜᴇᴍ ᴄᴏᴏʟ ᴀs ᴛᴏxɪɴ ᴄᴀɴ sᴘɪᴋᴇ ᴛʜᴇɪʀ ᴛᴇᴍᴘᴇʀᴀᴛᴜʀᴇ 
 
↠ɴᴏᴡ ɪsɴᴛ ᴛʜᴇ ᴛɪᴍᴇ ᴛᴏ ʙᴀʙʏ ʏᴏᴜʀ ᴅᴏɢ, ɢɪᴠᴇ ᴛʜᴇᴍ ᴛʜᴇ ʜᴇʟᴘ ᴛʜᴇʏ ɴᴇᴇᴅ ᴀsᴀᴘ, ᴇᴠᴇɴ ɪғ ᴛʜᴇʏ ғɪɢʜᴛ ᴀɴᴅ ᴄʀʏ, ʙᴇ ᴄᴀʀᴇғᴜʟ ᴀs ᴛʜᴇʏ ᴍᴀʏ ʟᴀsʜ ᴏᴜᴛ ᴀɴᴅ ʙɪᴛᴇ 
 
↠ᴛʜᴇ sᴏᴏɴᴇʀ ʏᴏᴜ ʀᴇᴄᴏɢɴɪᴢᴇ sʏᴍᴘᴛᴏᴍs ᴛʜᴇ ʙᴇᴛᴛᴇʀ. ᴛʜᴇ ᴄᴏɴᴅɪᴛɪᴏɴs ᴡɪʟʟ ᴡᴏʀsᴇɴ ʙᴇғᴏʀᴇ ᴛʜᴇʏ ɢᴇᴛ ʙᴇᴛᴛᴇʀ. ᴅᴏ ɴᴏᴛ ᴘᴀɴɪᴄ. 

↠ғɪʀsᴛ 30ᴍɪɴs ɪs ᴀ sᴡɪғᴛ ᴅᴏᴡɴᴡᴀʀᴅ ᴛʀᴇɴᴅ. ɪғ ʏᴏᴜ ᴄᴀᴜɢʜᴛ ɪᴛ ᴇᴀʀʟʏ, ᴀɴᴅ ᴀᴅᴍɪɴɪsᴛᴇʀᴇᴅ ᴘʀᴏᴘᴇʀ ᴄᴀʀᴇ, ʜᴏᴘᴇғᴜʟʟʏ, ᴀғᴛᴇʀ ᴀɴ ʜᴏᴜʀ ᴛʜᴇ ᴅᴏᴡɴᴡᴀʀᴅ ᴛʀᴇɴᴅ sʜᴏᴜʟᴅ sᴛᴏᴘ ᴀɴᴅ ᴛʜᴇ ᴄᴏɴᴅɪᴛɪᴏɴ sʜᴏᴜʟᴅ sᴛᴀʙʟɪᴢᴇ. 

↠ᴅᴏ ɴᴏᴛ ᴀᴛᴛᴇᴍᴘᴛ ᴛᴏ ғᴇᴇᴅ ᴏʀ ɢɪᴠᴇ ʏᴏᴜʀ ᴅᴏɢ ᴡᴀᴛᴇʀ ᴛᴏ ᴅʀɪɴᴋ, ᴛʜᴇʏ ᴀʀᴇ ɴᴏᴛ ᴏᴜᴛ ᴏғ ᴛʜᴇ ᴡᴏᴏᴅs. ᴍᴏɴɪᴛᴏʀ ᴄʟᴏsᴇʟʏ, ᴛʜᴇ ғᴏʟʟᴏᴡɪɴɢ ᴍᴏʀɴɪɴɢ ɢɪᴠᴇ ᴛʜᴇᴍ ᴛᴡᴏ ᴍᴏʀᴇ ᴄʜᴀʀᴄᴏᴀʟ ᴛᴀʙs ᴀɴᴅ ɢᴇᴛ ᴛʜᴇᴍ ᴛᴏ ᴀ ᴠᴇᴛ ᴀsᴀᴘ.

The Cane Toad was introduced into Gordonvale Queensland 22km south of Cairns in 1935 from Hawaii to combat the sugar cane beetle which was destroying the crops of the sugarcane industry. It has since hopped all over Queensland and is now entering neighbouring states. The Toad is presently considered a major pest and threat to native wildlife. All efforts are now being made for its eradication. The skin of the Cane Toad is strong, tough and durable and makes up into excellent leather goods.

Chinese medicine manufacturers have been using the Toads for centuries in the treatment of Cardio Vascular Diseases and Cancer treatment. It is highly likely that the Cane Toad will one day be farmed in Queensland in high volume for production of therapeutic medicines for mankind. A reversal - from pest to life saver.

Os magos, porém, usaram suas artes mágicas para imitar a praga e também fizeram aparecer rãs sobre a terra do Egito.
Êxodo 8:7 NVT

À procura do que escrever me lembrei dessa passagem bíblica. Os magos, consultores espirituais do faraó, conseguiam reproduzir, por meio de magias, a praga; porém, não conseguiram evita-la nem cessa-la.

Mais adiante, faraó faz um pedido: Então o faraó convocou Moisés e Arão e disse: “Supliquem ao Senhor que afaste as rãs de mim e de meu povo. (...)”.
Êxodo 8:8 NVT. 

Ele não pediu aos magos que, com a praga também sofreram, apesar de suas magias e súplicas a seus deuses!!!! 

A praga cessou, por meio da oração de Moisés, no período pedido pelo faraó, com um propósito: 
“Que seja amanhã”, disse o faraó. “Será como o faraó disse”, respondeu Moisés. “Então saberá que não há ninguém como o Senhor, nosso Deus.
Êxodo 8:10 NVT

Desejo que não seja necessário vir rãs na sua vida para que seja necessário reconhecer que "não há ninguém como o Senhor, nosso Deus". 😉🐸

Spent some time staring into the eyes of 200 million years of evolution today! This cane toad is the distant relative of a native South American toad but it’s direct descendant was one of 102 that was brought to Australia due to research done by the Queensland government in 1935 ,To try and eradicate the white grub which was hindering some Queensland sugar cane farmers profits! This is a poisonous toad and is now responsible for an unknown amount of extinction of Australia’s natural fauna due to spending their last 200 million years having nothing to do with South America or its deadly toad, a wonderful place but quite adequately separated by a vast amount of ocean that guaranteed no animal in Australia had grown to know the toxic death this toad would give it . There are now an estimated 200 million cane toads in Australia. They were introduced by a Queensland government entomologist Reginald Mungomery but his research was refuted by the aptly named Walter Froggatt saying that they had the ability and hardiness to become a toxic and wide spread invasive species and the deployment of cane toads was halted. Only to be overturned by the most toxic and powerfully invasive white grub of the land , the prime minister of Australia , Joseph Lyons who was persuaded by sugar cane lobbyists who were and still are big business to overturn the ban . I suppose this is just another unfortunate example and maybe a reason why not to trust a joint decision of government and big business. Another common invasive species in Florida is the cane toad which can also be known as the bufo, giant or marine toad. 

Cane toads are often poisonous to most of the things that they try to bite so the FWC allows people to kill these toads when located on your property. 

Cane toads are native to South America along the Amazon basin. They were first introduced to Florida in the 1930s as a way to control pests in sugarcane. However, the large increase in population is believed to be caused by escapes and releases of these toads by pet owners in the 1950s.

Large, bumpy, carnivorous, and toxic from egg to adult, the cane toad is a formidable creature—and an infamous example of an invasive species. Found in Central and South America, the cane toad was deliberately introduced into Australia, Hawaii, Philippines, Puerto Rico, and South Florida as part of a strategy to combat cane beetles, which were decimating agricultural crops. The toads instead ate native insects—and any other prey that would fit in their mouths, but not the intended target. This reduced food sources for native insectivores, throwing ecosystems out of balance. Cane toads are also difficult to manage as they are equipped with poison glands that secrete a toxic substance when they are threatened. Biological controls can be an environmentally-friendly way to control pests, but great care and extensive research must be taken before releasing them. It's important to look before you leap. #InvasiveSpeciesWeek #InvasiveSpecies #CaneToad #Toad

A carousel of frogs to start the week. The Red-eyed Tree Frog was shot in Berkshire and was a customs seizure from Heathrow.  It was photographed around 20 years ago and has been one of my best selling pictures. The Red-backed Poison Dart Frog was taken in the Amazon, while the Panamanian Golden Frogs are probably now extinct in the wild. The Cane Toad is the bad guy in this series. Photographed 3 yrs ago in the Solomon Islands in the South Pacific these toads were released to control pests in Palm Oil plantations and have now spread and are now munching their way through the native frog populations of the islands. The final shot was taken in the Caucasus in Georgia where I got snowed in for a week but it did not matter as there was plenty to photograph not just birds but lots of Marsh Frogs intent on reaching ponds that started to thaw.

It's Day 22 of #writes4womenchallenge and the theme is memorable villains. Be careful of the undertoad...is the haunting refrain in John Irving's "The World According to Garp". A lurking villain that never shows its face, the undertoad is always waiting to pull you under and suck you out to the depths.  The undertoad (a child's mistaken word for undertow) comes to represent all those anxieties and fears that plague us, the sense that something bad might always happen no matter how brightly the sun is shining, no matter how benign the swell appears. The undertoad is every dread in one menacing package, the perfect villain in my book. This is a cane toad and it is deadly to your dog! 

It can look similar to toad we have here in St. Augustine Fl but, as of now it does not live this far north. The farthest north it has been found is Volusia but, it is very rare there. It’s is frequently found from Orange County and south. 

If your dog licks this toad you need to seek immediate medical care from a veterinarian. Go immediately to the ER any time of day or night! 

The first sign is non-specific foaming at the mouth and drooling which can happen from many things but, the next sign is rapid decline-seizures, heart failure, vomiting and all variations of these signs. 

A good resource for more information and what to do if you find one is https://ufwildlife.ifas.ufl.edu/frogs/canetoad.shtml

❌Cane Toads are one of Australia’s most common and prevalent pests, introduced to the country in 1935. Cane Toads pose a particular threat to pets. This is due to the venom-secreting poison glands ☠️ where the poison is released when they are threatened or attacked❌

Identification:
Cane Toads can be identified by their grey, yellow or brown colouration and pale spotted belly. They are relatively large and heavily built amphibians with bumpy, warty skin. 

Activity:
Cane Toads are most active primarily at night. 🌕 They tend to be more prevalent during the warmer summer months ☀️ and wet conditions (heavy rainfall) 🌧 

Are Cane Toads still poisonous when dead?
Cane Toads are poisonous ☠️ at all stages of life; from tadpoles all the way until they are dead and dried. If you come across a dead Cane Toad, it is important to dispose of it properly - buried so animals cannot dig it up, or throwing it in the bin 🗑

Side effects of ingesting Cane Toad poison:
- Salivation 🤤 or foaming at the mouth 
- Vomiting 🤮 
- Pawing at mouth 
- Dilated pupils 👀 
- Increase in heart rate ♥️ 
- Convulsions and paralysis 
- Seizures 
- High body temperature 🤒 
- Death 💀 

Preventative measures:
- If your dog lives outside, use raised bowls to stop Toads coming in contact with food and water 
- When taking your pet out for a toilet break 🚽, monitor them closely with a torch 🔦 to make sure they are safe 
- Methods of humane euthanasia are also possible (traps, HopStop or stepped hypothermia)

What to do if your pet has ingested Cane Toad poison:
- Use a wet cloth to wipe out their mouth until the slimy coating from the Toad has been removed 
- Flushing out the mouth with water - ❌ Be careful when doing this so as to not have the dog inhale water - this can cause pneumonia ❌
- If pet is showing symptoms of Cane Toad poisoning them to the vet IMMEDIATELY 🩺 

DISCLAIMER❌information reworded - taken from various sources❌

turning toads into treasure 🐸💚> meet Lia Tabrah @ottbyliat from @vermin_the_label on the latest edition of our creative women series.

before the pandemic, you might remember we were invited to participate in #ToadBusting, an exciting exhibition organised by VERMIN, which explored the notion & possibilities of turning cane toads, a well-known Australian pest into something more appreciated. 

artists covering various art forms used cane toad leather as part of their usual practice & showcased the works as part of the exhibition. for the event, we reimagined one of our signature shapes, & created the L Thick Crescent Moon in what we’re calling a Dark Chocolate Toad hue [head to our stories for the shop link].

VERMIN are currently on a journey to create their own tanning facility that turns Australia’s own top end pests into the leather. currently there are no other tanneries turning Aussie toads into Aussie leather. working with Australia’s First Nations groups, Lia Tabrah & Perina Drummond are the forces behind the brand making it all happen. 

inherently a visual artist & maker of jewellery with a bold & humorous Australiana 80’s aesthetic, Lia’s creative journey has led her to working with the ‘grotesque’ cane toad. we caught up with Lia to discover how this has evolved in her practice & how her connection to country has influenced her creative practice more broadly.

~ Wednesday Wildlife fact ~

Introducing Bruce, Nanny McPhee & Helga our Cane Toads. 

Cane toads were introduced to Australia in 1935. They were brought to Australia from Hawaii with the intention to control the cane beetle in sugar cane fields in north Queensland. Only 102 cane toads were brought over to be bred, and 2,400 toads were released in 1935.

It seemed like a great idea at first, however, the cane beetles and the cane toads rarely crossed paths as the cane beetles lived up the stalk of the cane plant, and cane toads can’t jump that high so they barely had any effect!

Cane toads are toxic at all life stages - from eggs to adults. This is bad news for Australia’s native species, as they haven’t had time to adapt to these toad toxins. One lick or bite can cause native animals to experience rapid heartbeats, excessive salivation, convulsions, paralysis and death.

Each female cane toad can lay 35,000 eggs twice a year. There is now an estimated 200 million cane toads living in Australia. Adult cane toads compete with native wildlife for both food and shelter. There is a way to humanly kill these pests and that is by putting them into a bag and placing them in the fridge for several hours, then transferring them into the freezer. The toads quietly slip into unconsciousness and freeze.

CANE TOAD ALERT❕

We have had a few cases come in with Cane Toad toxicity of late. 

All toads are POISONOUS to dogs.
Their toxin has been know to kill frogs, snakes, goannas, quolls and even crocodiles. They are poisonous from eggs to tadpoles to adults and even dead dried cane toads can be deadly.

Poisoning can occur when a dog comes in contact with the toad through "mouthing" the toad - through biting or licking. When the toad is attacked or threatened they release a potent and fast acting toxin from their large poison glands. 
 
Signs and symptoms:
*Drooling or foaming at the mouth
*Red and slimy gums
*Vomiting
*Pawing at the mouth
*Disorientation
*Dilated pupils
*Increased heart rate
*Panting or difficulty breathing
*Seizures
*High body temperature
*Death

If your dog has licked, bitten or eaten a cane toad, it is vital you get them to a vet IMMEDIATELY. 
Do NOT use a hose to flush their mouth-as this can make them inhale water which can lead to pneumonia (or downing).

If you believe your pet is showing any of the above signs or symptoms you can use a damp cloth to wipe the inside of their mouth until the slimy coating has been removed. Then take them to a vet immediatley.

The weekend Rio Grande Valley trip was largely a bust. I didn’t see any rare birds and the reptile and amphibian activity was extremely limited. That was predictable due to a combination of timing, lack of recent rainfall, and we’d used up most of our good luck earlier in the month. However, Erin and I did find our first Cane Toad. Not a huge one and a bit beat up (look at them toes) but pretty cool observation.
.
Cane toads just range into South Texas as part of their native range. A fact many never learn. This is a species that has a bad wrap. They can be extremely invasive and have colonized sites around the world – as a consequence of human activity.
.
I’ll be honest. I didn’t think about Cane Toad when I was considering all the cool frogs, toads, and salamanders I wanted to target from the Valley as part of my Texas Herping Big Year 2021. Cane Toad just never came to mind. I flat out forgot about them. Until I literally had one swim over to me while scanning the banks of a resaca at Bentsen Rio Grande Valley State Park. It ended up being an unexpected treat. This is the fifth new species of herp (reptiles and amphibians) I’ve seen since starting my Texas herping big year project!

The skin of the cane toad is dry and warty. Distinct ridges above the eyes run down the snout.

A large parotoid gland lies behind each eye. The pupils are horizontal and the irises golden.

The toes have a fleshy webbing at their base, and the fingers are free of webbing.

🐸 #canetoad #bufotoxin ☠️What makes cane toads toxic? Thanks so much @naturalwanderscomics for all the great questions! Rhinella marina, pictured above, is a large neotropical toad from South America with a voracious appetite! It has been introduced around the world to control sugarcane pests, hence it’s common name, the cane toad! Bufadienolide, pictured above, is a steroid bufotoxin aglycone. It is excreted from the alveoli of the parotid gland when the toad needs to defend itself. When bound to a sugar, bufadienolide becomes a cardiac glycoside, inactivating sodium/potassium ATP-ase pumps in the myocardial sarcolemma, the tissue responsible for heart contractions. Inactivation leads to a buildup of ions inside the heart cell (swipe to see! The red arrows indicate blocked activity!) Potassium can still compete for pump reactivation if the bufadienolide dose is low enough; when reactivated, the higher calcium content of the cell will lead to a more foreceful positive inotropic contraction! This mechanism is used in traditional and Western medicine to treat arrythmia and heart failure without affecting blood pressure. Bufadienolide has a very narrow therapeutic window; if the dose is above .2 nanograms per milliliter of blood, the potassium ion will not reactivate the pump, resulting in dysrhythmia, fibrilliation, and potentially fatal heart block! This venom is so concentrated and dangerous, very few predators will dare to eat this toxic toad, allowing it to aggressively expand into new territory. Contrary to popular belief, cane toads do NOT contain the psychadelic tryptamine bufotenin, so please don’t lick them!!! Discuss in the comments below!

The first QLD Cane Toad has appeared near our clinic. 

Cane toads were introduced into #australia decades ago to help control a certain beetle, but they are very toxic to pets. 

The NSW toads are thought to have arrived through a freight truck, please keep alert for #canetoads in your area.

Symptoms of #canetoad poisoning include: frothing at the mouth, vomiting, itching, coughing, high body temperature and lethargy. 

If you see Cane Toads in your area please contact the Department of Primary Industries. 

If you suspect your pet is sick from a cane toad interaction, please come straight to the clinic or message 0406 9 DR SAM.

We will keep monitoring the situation and our most up to date recommendations will be posted here on #Instagram

Sometimes we can over-romanticise nature. Nature can be cruel. Not deliberately vindictive, but cruel. I was tenderly watching the egret that comes to my garden. So elegant. So beautiful. Before my eyes he grabbed this cane toad and shook it violently, then dropped it, stunned. As it lay temporarily dazed the egret plucked out it's eye. It happened so fast I thought the bird had quickly killed the toad with a swift stab of it's sabre beak. I went to look and found the toad very alive, standing high on it's front legs in a defense pose - unscathed in body, but one eye missing and a thread of tissue protruding from the vacant space. I'm seeing that egret in a whole new light. The toad's skin is quite poisonous. The bird must know that.

It is important to seek veterinary help immediately, as an average sized dog can die within 15 minutes of coming into contact with a large amount of the toxin.”

Cane "Marine" Toad
(Rhinella marina)
The Cane Toad is the largest species of toad in the world and is Native to South and Central America as well as being invasive in places such as the Caribbean and Australia as they were released to these areas to help control invasive pests such as the Sugar Cane Beetle.  Those big bulbous areas behind it's head are toxin glands and when it feels threatened, it produces a toxin that is deadly to medium and small animals which narrows down this toads predators. 

Special Thanks to Jesse Rybicki for allowing me to come out and photograph this guy.
